Getting to know Your Cube:

Notations And Turns

There are multiple notations for the different turns for the Rubik's Cube. The are 3 different notations for each side and there six different sides so there are 18 different notations in total. The sides are: Up, Down, Left, Right, Front, and Back. U stands for Up, D stands for Down, L stands for Left, R stands for Right F stands for Front, and B stands for Back. All turns are clockwise unless told otherwise. If a turn is counterclockwise then the notation will have a i in behind of it. There is one more type of turn. Some people might think it's 2 turns but when solving rubik's cubes it's 1 turn. It's a turn that is a 180. If there is the notation with the number 2, then it is a 180. For example U2 or F2.

Solving the First Layer:

White Cross

This part is the easiest, so you might be able to do this one your own. There are two ways to do this. You can put the edges in the correct spot in the first place or you can put then with the white. If the edges are with the white with the on the edge faces up but the other color is not matching do this.

Keep on doing a U turn until at least 2 edges are in the correct spot. The edges that are not in the correct spot must be in the front and on the right. Then do these turns

F2, D, R2, Di, F2

The White cross

Solving the First Layer:

White Corners

There are 2 ways things that can happen when solving the white corners. The first figure is when the white corner is in the bottom layer. The second figure is when the white corner is in the top layer

Figure 1

Di, Ri, D, R

It doesn't matter which figure is one the rubik's cube, just keep on doing this algorithm.

Figure 2

Solving the Middle Layer

Before we start this step, turn the rubik's cube so that the yellow side is facing upwards.

This part is harder then the past steps. There are 2 different things that could happen when doing the middle layer. The first figure is where the edge piece is on the top side. The second figure is where the edge piece is in the middle layer. No matter what the edge piece must be in the correct position or else this will not work. It will be in the correct position when the color on the top side is across it's colors side.

When you have the edge piece in the right spot, keep turning the cube until the edge piece is in the back.

Figure 1

R, F, U, Di, Ri, F, Ui, Fi

Keep turning the cube so it's in the back right position.

B, R, Ui, Ri, Bi, Ui, Fi, U, F, U2, R, F, U, Fi, Ri, F, Ui, Fi

Figure 2

Solving the Last Layer:

Solving the Edges

There are 3 different situations that can happen here. All three figures will use the same algorithm. The first figure is when there are no edges with yellow faces up. The second figure is when there are 2 edges in a straight line with yellow facing up. The third figure is when the are 2 edges in a shape of a the letter L have yellow facing up.

The algorithm is F, U, R, Ui, Ri, Fi,

Solving the Last Layer:

Solving the Yellow Corners

There are 3 different situations that can happen here. The first figure is when there are 2 corners with yellow facing upwards. There are different ways this can happen just as long there's a corner facing in the correct direction. The second figure is when there is 1 corner with yellow facing upwards. The third figure is when there are no corners with yellow facing upwards.

There must be a corner in the bottom left with yellow on the left

If you see a fish, then pretend that you have fish food in your left hand and it's eating the food so the mouth of the fish must be in bottom left.

Once you have the yellow side alligned in one of these way do the following

R, U, Ri, F, R, U2, Fi

Figure 3

Figure 1

Figure 2

Solving the Last Layer:

Aligning the Yellow Corners

Almost there. There are multiple things that can happen here, but there are 2 simple things that can happen. The first figure is when the are two corner together that are aligned. The second figure is when there are no corners that are aligned together.

The aligned corners must be in the back for this to work

Once you have the corners, do the following:

Ri, F, Ri, B2, R, Fi, Ri, B2, R2

This is just one of the examples, there are no corners together and aligned.

Solving the Last Layer:

Aligning the Yellow Edges

The Last Step

ALMOST THERE!!! There are 2 things that can happen here. The first figure is when there isn't a edge piece with its corners. The second figure is when there is a edge piece with it's corner. The edge piece with its corners must be in the back. For figure 2 depending on how it is depends on what algorithm you use. If the color on the center piece of the front face matches the color of the edge piece on the left then have the U turns in the algorithm be counterclockwise but if the color on the center piece of the front face matches the color of the edge piece on the right, then have the U turns in the algorithm be clockwise.

Figure 1

If the color on the center piece of the front face matches the color of the edge piece on the left then have the U turns in the algorithm be counterclockwise

F2, Ui, L, Ri, F2, R, Li, Ui, F2

If the color on the center piece of the front face matches the color of the edge piece on the right, then have the U turns in the algorithm be clockwise and visa versa. The corner and edge pieces that are together correctly must be in he back.

F2, Ui, L, Ri, F2, R, Li, Ui, F2

Figure 2
